Business Overview and Objectives¶

Bankruptcy prediction is an important problem in finance, since successful predictions would allow stakeholders to take early actions to limit their economic losses. In recent years many studies have explored the application of machine learning models to bankruptcy prediction with financial ratios as predictors.

The goal of this case study is to build a Random Forest Model and a XGBoost Model using historical financial data to predict which companies are likely to be bankrupted and evaluate which variables are most important to determine the bankruptcy. These predictions will be used by the finance division of investment firms to divest of companies in advance that would cause significant losses in the future.

Data Evaluation and Engineering¶

Raw dataset:

  • The raw dataset is collected over five years in the format of .arff files. The size of each file is:
    • 1year.arff contains financial rates from 1st year of the forecasting period. It contains 7,027 observations with 65 variables.
    • 2year.arff contains financial rates from 2nd year of the forecasting period. It contains 10,173 observations with 65 variables.
    • 3year.arff contains financial rates from 3rd year of the forecasting period. It contains 10,503 observations with 65 variables.
    • 4year.arff contains financial rates from 4th year of the forecasting period. It contains 9,792 observations with 65 variables.
    • 5year.arff contains financial rates from 5th year of the forecasting period. It contains 5,910 observations with 65 variables.
  • Meta data is provided for all features descriptions.

The team started the process by combining those 5 files together into a dataframe. We then wrote the data to a simple csv file for a more convinience way to use it in the future. After that, we mapped the meta data to all features to make it easy to read and interpret.

Data Description:

  • There is a total of 43,405 observation in the dataset.
  • The dataset contains 64 features (Attr1 to Attr 64). All features are continuous variables.
  • The target variable is called 'class' with 2 values: b'0' for Non-bankrupt and b'1' for Bankrupt. We then mapped the target variable b'0' to 0 and b'1' to 1 to make it simple to be used in our models.
    • 41,314 observations for b'0' or 0 or Non-bankrupt class
    • 2,091 observations for b'1' or 1 or Bankrupt class

# Read in all 5 years record then combine to one dataset
df = pd.DataFrame()

for i in range(1,6):
    path = 'Data/' + str(i) + 'year.arff'
    data = arff.loadarff(path)
    data = pd.DataFrame(data[0])
    df = pd.concat([df, data], ignore_index=True, sort=False)
    print(i,'year.arff data shape:', data.shape)

Missing Values:

  • There is no missing value in the target variable -- Yeah!
  • All features have at least one missing value. (As shown in the shape of df_na in the code below with 64 rows.)
  • Top 5 missing values features are:
    • 'Attr37' or 'X37 (current assets - inventories) / long-term liabilities' has 18,984 missing values or 43.7% missing
    • 'Attr21' or 'X21 sales (n) / sales (n-1)' has 5,854 missing values or 13.5% missing
    • 'Attr27' or 'X27 profit on operating activities / financial expenses' has 2,764 missing values or 6.4% missing
    • 'Attr60' or 'X60 sales / inventory' has 2,152 missing values or 5.0% missing
    • 'Attr45' or 'X45 net profit / inventory' has 2,147 missing values or 4.9% missing
  • To drop all missing values from the dataset, we will lost more than half of the observations. We decided to keep all observations by looking at the compromise way to manipulate all missing values.

# Count missing values
df_na = pd.DataFrame(df.isna().sum())
df_na.rename(columns={df_na.columns[0]: 'count'}, inplace = True)

df_na = df_na[df_na['count'] != 0]
df_na['percent_missing'] = df_na['count']/df.shape[0]
df_na = df_na.sort_values('count', ascending=False)

# Using Textwrap for chart axis due to long feature names
import textwrap
def wrap_labels(ax, width, break_long_words=False):
    labels = []
    for label in ax.get_xticklabels():
        text = label.get_text()
        labels.append(textwrap.fill(text, width=width, break_long_words=break_long_words))
    ax.set_xticklabels(labels, rotation=90)

# Using Textwrap for chart axis due to long feature names
def wrap_labels0(ax, width, break_long_words=False):
    labels = []
    for label in ax.get_xticklabels():
        text = label.get_text()
        labels.append(textwrap.fill(text, width=width, break_long_words=break_long_words))
    ax.set_xticklabels(labels, rotation=0)

Data Manipulation¶

Random Forest model requires a completed dataset, which mean that we cannot have any missing values in the dataset. In this case, we need to replace all the missing values with:

  • Since all features are continuous, we decided to fill in the missing value for each feature with its mean.
  • However, With extreme outlier in the 10 high std feature mention above, we decided to fill the missing values in those feature with their median value instead. This is to make sure that the eactreme outliers will not affect the fill-in values.
In [ ]:
feature_data = df.copy()
feature_data.drop(["class"], axis=1, inplace=True)

mean_replace_cols = list(feature_data.columns.difference(outlier_df.columns))
median_replace_cols = list(outlier_df.columns)
In [ ]:
full_df = df.copy()

# Replace missing values in numerical variables with its mean.
for col in mean_replace_cols:
    full_df[col].fillna(full_df[col].mean(), inplace=True)

# Replace missing values in numerical variables with its median.
for col in median_replace_cols:
    full_df[col].fillna(full_df[col].median(), inplace=True)

Classification Models¶

To approach the objectives of this case study, we decided to use Decision Tree Algorithm. There are multiple advantages of the algorithm that we aould like to mention here:

  • It can be used to solve both regression and classification problems.
  • It requires less effort for data preparation during pre-processing. It does not require normalization of data as well.
  • It is very intuitive and easy to explain to technical teams as well as stakeholders.
  • Missing values in the data also do NOT affect the process of building a decision tree in some types of models.

There are 2 decision tree models that we are proposing for this classification:

Random Forest¶

The random forest is a classification algorithm consisting of many decisions trees. It uses bagging and feature randomness when building each individual tree to try to create an uncorrelated forest of trees whose prediction by committee is more accurate than that of any individual tree.

In conclusion, Random forest is a collection of trees in which each of them gives a prediction and finally, we collect the outputs from all the trees and considers the mean, median, or mode of this collection as the prediction of this forest depending upon the nature of data (either continues or categorical).

XGBoost (eXtreme Gradient Boosting)¶

XGBoost is a decision-tree-based ensemble Machine Learning algorithm that uses a gradient boosting framework. XGBoost was developed to increase speed and performance, while introducing regularization parameters to reduce overfitting. Gradient boosted trees use regression trees (or CART) in a sequential learning process as weak learners.

Image Credits: https://dataaspirant.com
¶

To prepare, build, evaluate and interpret these 2 models, we follow the steps below:¶

Model Preparation and Model Building¶

  1. We splitted the dataset into 90% of the dataset to the train and 10% to the validation (or test) dataset. To make sure that we have the validate dataset that is not invaded by model building process.
    • We used train_test_split function from sklearn
    • Random Forest requires completed dataset without missing values. So we used the maipulated dataset, which called 'full_df' to build the Random Forest model.
    • XGBoost model can handle a dataset with missing velues. So we will use the original dataset with all missing values include, called 'df' to build the XGBoost model.
  2. ColumnTransformer using StandardScaler is used to scale all features. Compiling this with Pipeline function from sklearn to make sure that there is no leakage between train and test dataset.
  3. To find the best model parameters, we use RandomizedSearchCV. The RandomizedSearchCV, in contrast to GridSearchCV, not all parameter values are tried out, but rather a fixed number of parameter settings is sampled from the specified distributions. This can help us save tremendous amount on computational cost. ### Model Evaluation
  4. We then fitted the model best parameter to the train dataset using coss_validation (cv=5).
  5. Finally, we made prediction on the test dataset using the model. To evaluate model performance, we used the following 4 matrices: Accuracy, Precision, Recall, and F1-score. We will discuss about this in more detail in the next section. We also use these 4 matrices to determine which model performs better, between Random FOrest and XGBoost ### Model Interpretation
  6. After all, we looked at the most important features for each model to see which variables are most important to determine the bankruptcy.

Model Evaluation¶

To evaluate the models, there are 4 model matrics evaluation that we included:

1) Accuracy: Model accuracy is defined as the number of classifications a model correctly predicts divided by the total number of predictions made. In other words, 'what percent of our prediction is right?'|.

$$ Accuracy = \frac{TP+TN}{ALL} $$

2) Precision: The precision measures the model's performance in classifying a sample as positive. In other words, 'what percent of bankruptcy prediction were corrected?'.

$$ Precision = \frac{TP}{TP+FP} $$

3) Recall: The recall measures the model's ability to detect Positive samples. The higher the recall, the more positive samples detected. In other words, 'what percent of bankruptcy did ee catch?'.

$$ Recall = \frac{TP}{TP+FN} $$

4) F1 Score: The F1-score combines the precision and recall of a classifier into a single metric by taking their harmonic mean. In other words, 'it is an average of presicion and recall'.

$$ F1-Score = \frac{2 * Precision * Recall}{Precision + Recall} $$
Image Credits: https://blog.paperspace.com/
¶

Trade-Off¶

Out of all 4 matrices above, we would prefer the model that provides a higher recall, even if other matrices are relatively low.

Understanding that the model will not be perfect in correctly identifying potetnital companies that may go bankrupt.
It was decided that recall was the metric of choice in this case because, the objective was to identify potetnital companies that may be go bankrupt.

The recall metic was in the best intrest of the objective, because recall, in relation to precision, ensures more companies that ACTUALLY go bankrupt are correctly identified by the model as at risk.
Accepting that selecting a model based on recall, may also incorrectly identify a company that does NOT go bankrupt as at risk.

It is recommended in conjunction with the model, a buisness analayst treats the model output as preliminary list of companies that they should review prior to any action being taken.
Reviewing a list of a few companies wondering which comapny is a false positive, is a smaller problem than, serching thousands of companies wondering which company is a false negative.

Given that, the cost and likely hood of staying invested in a company that goes bankrupt is greater than potetnitally un-investing from a company that doesn't go bankrupt.

# Create scorer for those 4 matrices mentioned above.
scorer = {
    'accuracy': make_scorer(accuracy_score),
    'precision': make_scorer(precision_score, average='macro'),
    'recall': make_scorer(recall_score, average='macro'), 
    'F1': make_scorer(f1_score, average='macro')
}

    print("%0.3f (+/-%0.03f) for %r" % (mean, std * 2, params))
print()

6. Most Important Features to Determine the Bankruptcy.¶

Top 5 most important features for XGBoost model are:

  • Feature45 or 'X45 net profit / inventory'
  • Feature57 or 'X57 (current assets - inventory - short-term liabilities) / (sales - gross profit - depreciation)'
  • Feature4 or 'X4 current assets / short-term liabilities'
  • Feature26 or 'X26 (net profit + depreciation) / total liabilities'
  • Feature33 or 'X33 operating expenses / short-term liabilities'

Conclusions and Discussions¶

Conclusions¶

  • The goal of this case study was to build a classification model using historical financial data to predict which companies are likely to be bankrupted and evaluate which variables are most important to determine the bankruptcy. These predictions will be used by the finance division of investment firms to divest of companies in advance that would cause significant losses in the future.
  • Missing values were present in every feature of the dataset, although some features contained more missing values than others.
  • There were also some features that have significant outliers.
  • Since Random Forest model requires completed dataset without missing value. To fill in the missing values; For the columns where there were not any outliers the mean was used, for the columns where there were outliers the median was used. Median was used to fill missing values in the columns where an outlier occurred, because it is more resilient to outliers than the mean.
  • A random forest model and an XGBoost model were used to categorize companies that were at risk of bankruptcy or not at risk.
  • Recall was selected over precision to determine the most useful approach between Random Forest and XGBoost. This was decided because the cost of potentially incorrectly flagging a company as at risk for bankruptcy could be mitigated by having a business analyst review the model output prior to taking action. Mitigating the risk of recall made it less expensive than failing to identify a bankrupt company as bankrupt.
  • Expecting a business analyst to identify companies at risk for bankruptcy that the model missed is like looking for a needle a haystack. To save a business analyst time and to limit the number of companies that went bankrupt but were missed by the model recall was chosen.
  • The XGBoost model was the best performing model with a recall of .83 compared to a recall of .62 for the Random Forest model.
  • This means that if there are 10 companies as bankrupt XGBoost model will flag 8 companies out of the 10 companies, while the Random Forest model will flag only 6 companies.
  • XGBoost model has better performance for all 4 matrices in comparison to the Random Forest model, as shown in the table below:
XGBoost Random Forest
Accuracy .97 .96
Precision .88 .86
Recall .83 .62
F1-score .85 .67
  • For XGBoost model the most important features in determining whether not a company will go bankrupt are:
    • 'X45 net profit / inventory'
    • 'X57 (current assets - inventory - short-term liabilities) / (sales - gross profit - depreciation)'
    • 'X4 current assets / short-term liabilities'
    • 'X26 (net profit + depreciation) / total liabilities'
    • 'X33 operating expenses / short-term liabilities'
    • Note: X45 and X26 are within the top 5 most important features for both models

Discussions¶

  • Given part of the objective included evaluating the most important metrics to determine bankruptcy, an interpretable model was required to determine an approach useful or not?
  • Having a domain expert to help clarify terms and features in this case study will be very helpful.
  • Other algorithms that can be useful for classification such as, Logistic Regression, KNN, etc. can be used for further research.
